  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's a real thing I've seen play out in my own life and in the community around me. Growing up with a parent who has a PhD and another who only went to lower secondary school, I've always been curious about how people think and why they act the way they do. My curiosity led me to read about stereotype threat, and it hit home when I saw how students from underrepresented groups, like my own kids who are in school, start to doubt themselves when they're in classrooms where STEM is seen as 'for the smart ones.' I've worked as a plumber for years, and I know how important it is to have people feel safe and confident in their abilities. When someone feels like they're not good enough because of a stereotype, it can really hold them back. But should we address it? Absolutely. I've volunteered at local schools, and I've seen how a simple conversation about what it means to be a 'good' plumber or a 'good' scientist can make a big difference. It's not about changing the system overnight—it's about small, personal interactions that build trust and confidence. My neuroticism makes me anxious about these things, but my curiosity drives me to look for solutions. I think the key is to start early, with kids in elementary school, and to create environments where everyone feels they belong. For example, in my community, we have a program where kids from diverse backgrounds work together on projects that show STEM isn't just for a select few. This approach helps break down stereotypes and builds a sense of belonging. It's not easy, but it's worth it. The goal is to make sure no one feels like they're failing because of a label they were given.",
